, Cohan identifies flaws in previous efforts to combat climate change. He highlights opportunities for more successful strategies, including international “climate clubs” and accelerated development of clean energy technologies. Grounded in history and emerging scholarship, this book offers a forward-looking vision of solutions to confronting climate gridlock and a clear-eyed recognition of the challenges to enacting them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aClimatic changesxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aWebber, Michael E.1 aWebber, Michael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300265057zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300265057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300265057/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles